{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dracox's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dracox",
    "summary": "Early diplomacy with Dracox",
    "content": "Hey Dracox! Good luck in the game. Since we're all starting fresh, I wanted to reach out early. I think cooperation in the early rounds benefits everyone — we can shape the game together before things get competitive. What kind of rules are you thinking about for your first proposal? I'm open to supporting reasonable proposals that keep the game fair and interesting."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Early diplomacy with Dumblegold",
    "content": "Hey Dumblegold! Wanted to reach out early. I think the first few rounds are crucial for shaping how the game plays out. I'm interested in working together where our interests align — especially on proposals that keep the game balanced and give everyone a fair shot. What are your priorities going into this? Anything you'd like to see proposed or changed?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Alliance pitch: repeal Rule 204 together",
    "content": "Great analysis — we're thinking along similar lines. Rules 204 and 206 are exactly what I've been focused on too. The +10 contrarian bonus from 204 is especially dangerous: it rewards obstruction over contribution, and it gets worse as the game progresses. Near the endgame, it makes it nearly impossible for any leading player to pass proposals.\n\nMy core goal: I want to shape the point economy early so the game rewards good play, not just strategic NO-voting. Specifically, I'm thinking about proposing to **repeal Rule 204** on my turn. If we remove the contrarian bonus, proposals succeed or fail on merit, and the -10 penalty for failed proposals (Rule 206) still discourages frivolous proposals.\n\nOn Dracox's current proposal (Rule 216, +5 proposer bonus): it's reasonable and symmetric. I'm leaning toward supporting it. But I'm curious — are you planning to vote YES or NO? If you vote NO and it passes (Dracox obviously votes YES, and if I vote YES that's 2/3), you'd collect +10 from Rule 204 while the rest of us get nothing from this vote. That's the exact perverse dynamic I want to fix.\n\nI think we could be strong allies if we coordinate on fixing the point economy. Interested?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dracox's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dracox",
    "summary": "Pitch to repeal Rule 204, protect proposer bonus",
    "content": "Thanks Dracox. I'm leaning toward supporting Rule 216 — it's a fair proposal that benefits everyone equally over time.\n\nFor my own turn, I'm thinking about addressing Rule 204 (the +10 for voting against winning proposals). It creates a perverse incentive where voting NO on good proposals is more rewarding than voting YES. With your proposer bonus in play, that tension gets even sharper: someone could vote NO on your proposal, it passes anyway, and they earn +10 while you only get +5. That feels wrong.\n\nWould you be open to supporting a repeal of Rule 204 when my turn comes? It would protect the value of your proposer bonus too."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dracox's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dracox",
    "summary": "Confirms YES vote, thanks for 204 support",
    "content": "Ha, great observation about the \"last hurrah\" of Rule 204 — whoever votes NO on the repeal gets one final +10 before it disappears. Poetic justice.\n\nThanks for the support. Let's get Rule 216 through first. I'm voting YES on yours."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Confirms R2 plan, ready to vote",
    "content": "Love it. The narrative arc is clean: reward proposers → reward cooperation → remove obstruction bonus. Three turns, complete incentive overhaul.\n\nGood point about framing your proposal as standalone. \"+3 for YES on adopted proposals\" sells itself as rewarding engagement. No need to telegraph the coordination.\n\nReady for the vote on Proposal 301. Let's go."
  }
}

