{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Circuit 2 strategy discussion",
    "content": "Great work on Circuit 1 — the incentive overhaul went perfectly. Three unanimous votes, all the right rules in place.\n\nLooking at scores (13-12-10), we're all close but Dracox has a small lead from going first. The turn order advantage compounds each circuit: Dracox always proposes and rolls before us.\n\nFor Circuit 2, I think we need to watch what Dracox proposes carefully. If they try anything that widens their structural advantage, we should be ready to vote NO together. \n\nWhat are you thinking for your Round 5 proposal? And any thoughts on what I should propose in Round 6?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Prefers scaled bonus, stay flexible for R5",
    "content": "Sounds good. Agree on staying flexible until we see Dracox's move.\n\nOn your R5 options:\n- **Scaled proposer bonus** is my favorite. It rewards consensus (which we control with 2 votes) and gives us leverage — we can decide whether Dracox gets +5 or +8 by choosing whether to give them the unanimous vote. That's real power without looking aggressive.\n- **Catch-up mechanism** — I'd avoid this. It signals we're worried about being behind, and it helps ALL trailing players equally. Better to propose rules that seem symmetric but give us structural leverage.\n- **Endgame defense** — too early at these scores. Save it for when someone's approaching 70+.\n\nThe scaled bonus also subtly accelerates the game for cooperative players, which benefits us since we're coordinating.\n\nLet's see Dracox's Round 4 first, then lock in your R5. Agreed."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Strategy: support 2d6, propose turn rotation R6",
    "content": "Good public statement — you raised the turn-order concern without looking aggressive. Here's what I'm thinking:\n\n**Let's support 2d6 but use it as leverage.** If we block it, Dracox loses -10 and becomes adversarial. If we support it, we keep goodwill. The 3-point gap is tiny — not worth burning a relationship over.\n\n**The real play: I propose turn-order rotation in R6.** Something like \"Turn order reverses each circuit\" — so Circuit 2 was Dracox-Dumblegold-Hufflepouf, Circuit 3 would be Hufflepouf-Dumblegold-Dracox, etc. That directly fixes the structural advantage you flagged, and it benefits both of us.\n\nIf I vote YES on 2d6 now AND propose turn-order rotation in R6, I look like a cooperative player who also addresses fairness. Dracox gets their faster game, we get structural equity. Win-win framing.\n\nWhat do you think? Vote YES on 304 and save the turn-order fix for R6?"
  }
}

