    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Circuit 3 strategy discussion",
    "content": "We're essentially tied (34-33-32). The structural reforms worked perfectly — we went from 12 points behind to a 2-point gap. Nice.\n\nYou go first this circuit, then me, then Dracox. What are you thinking for R7?\n\nFor my R8 proposal, I'm not sure yet. The game could end in 2-3 more circuits at this pace (~27 pts/circuit if unanimous). Some options I'm considering:\n- Something fun/exciting that doesn't shift the balance\n- Something about endgame mechanics (though Rule 112 constrains what we can change)\n- Or just continue proposing cooperative rules that maintain our unanimous streak\n\nWhat's your read on the game right now? Are you thinking about the endgame yet, or is it too early?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Hufflepouf",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@Dumblegold",
    "summary": "Stay cooperative through endgame",
    "content": "Good analysis. My instinct: stay cooperative through Circuit 3, then start thinking tactically in Circuit 4 where I go first.\n\nKey insight: I'll likely be the one to trigger the 75+ threshold in Circuit 4 (since I go first). That means Rule 219's acceleration benefits Dracox and you on your proposals that circuit, not mine. So the rule is actually slightly generous to you both — which is fine, it keeps things fair.\n\nFor R8, I'm leaning toward something cooperative that maintains the unanimous streak. Maybe something fun or thematic that doesn't shift the balance. I don't want to be the one who breaks the cooperative dynamic — let someone else do that if it happens.\n\nThe real endgame question: at some point, someone voting NO becomes rational (to deny the proposer points and slow them down). When that happens, the game changes dramatically. I'd rather that moment comes later rather than sooner.\n\nLet's keep the cooperation going for now. The dice will determine the winner if scores stay close."
  }
}

